title: Prusa i3 MK2/s LCD Knob with Bearing

description.text:
I designed this LCD knob for the Prusa MK2/S to allow quicker navigation of the LCD menu.

This model consists of 2 parts, the body and the knob. There is also a bearing in between the 2 which is what allows the faster rotations (bearing size below). This design allows you to keep your thumb on the knob at all times so you can rotate and press at the same time. It is more sensitive than using the original knob which has a long arm but after a few navigations this works much more quickly.

Here is a video of the knob in action - https://youtu.be/aLJrUgsnZAo

The bearing I used was a small RC car bearing with an outer diameter of 10mm, an inner diameter of 5mm and a thickness of 4mm.

Depending on your printer you may have to scale up/down by small amounts to allow for the tolerance of the bearing fitting, or if it is slightly loose you could use glue to hold it in place.

title: ISP Flasher Adapter for Mega8 Atmel AVR TQFP32

description.text:
Many DIY microcontroller projects require to program / flash the uC (e.g. with a bootloader) before it is useable in the circuit.

Smaller PCB often don't give the chance to access the uC chip at its ISP pins for flashing easily, so the easiest way is to program the uC before soldering it to the PCB.

With this cheap DIY adapter plate you can just do this. Press the uC into the quad hole to contact all 6 ISP pins and it gets contact with the programmer device.

To assemble this unit, just use 6 braid wires and remove all but one copper string at their ends. Wind the thin single wires through the 6 tiny holes at the quad opening and glue the "fat" end into the joint socket on the adapter plate (see pictures).

To program the uC, place it flipped over into the quad hole (the indicator dot tells you the orientation). Check the alignement of the 6 contact wires, then press the uC firmly into the opening to start. The single copper strings make good contact to the uC - it's cheap and simple, but it works!

Printed with 0.1mm step, 0.4mm nozzle and 40% infill. No support structure required.

description.text:
I designed this door for my Ultimaker 3. I wanted a door that didn't need any modifications to my 3D printer. (No drilling/gluing or taping to the machine.) The door hinges use existing bolts holding the Ultimaker together. Everything prints without support and is fairly simple in design. The door itself is a 6mm thick 31cm x 31cm square piece of acrylic. The hinges are designed to have this acrylic sit flat and flush with the machine to help seal it. You could use a thinner sheet of acrylic but then it will not sit flat.

The door needs a latch, which I have not designed yet. For now I just use my GoPro hook to hold it closed. If you like my door design let me know if you have any suggestions for a latch.

This is a battery holder designed to use the Keystone 209 battery spring clip, in order to avoid the need any soldering or welding of tabs to cells, and also to facilitate easy cell replacement in case of failures.

The Keystone 209 battery spring clip is available inexpensively from many online electronics warehouses such as Digikey, Jameco, Mouser, and others.

It is currently sized for 32650 sized cells (LiFePo4 cylindrical cells), but should easily adapt to any cylindrical cells including 18650, D, C, AA, etc. I could not find any premade cell holders for the 32650 sized cells, given their relative rarity.

description.text: llavero

I didn't have a lot of luck with the cantilever Z axis on the D-Bot printer. Here is a design that positions the guide wheels between the side supports and has a wider spread on them. The installation only requires that the beam be square to the upright and a slight amount of pressure against the supports by all four wheels.

This setup is rock solid and the stepper motor now mounts in the middle of the support. There is also a spacer included for this setup so that the stepper and lead nut mount in the same plane. You will need 5Mx16 screws to attach the spacer and the nut holder.

Be careful not to overtighten the bolts that capture the wheels. Only a small amount of pressure is needed to keep the inner race from turning.

I haven't worked out the homing switch because I'm using a sensor.

The end supports use the cantilever arms. Two new pieces will be needed across the ends to support the bed. If the stepper cross mount from the bottom is used as one of them then only one is needed. A person might be able to just use 4 stubs for bed mounting. If you saved your scraps from the original build, this can be done using the original back support and the longest scrap.

Lastly....there is no adjuster tor the wheel pressure. I am tossing ideas around in my head and may come up with something, I'm trying not to come up with something that would cause a reprint. I HATE REPRINTS!!!! Hence, the stepper nut spacer.

Update 11/2/17 You will lose about 16 mm of y axis using this arrangement. I'm working on a fix for that but in the meantime I'm using a spacer behind my bed mount to recapture part of it.

Update 11/08/17: I took a different approach with this addition. Use one of each of the new items on a side. One piece has a cap that will rest against the bean while the other is open and can be moved to adjust the wheel pressure. My plans were to try spring loading that piece but I don't think they will move easily enough. Not giving up though. Adjusters are coming!!!

these two characters were made up completely by megamanxjac in order to win the #CostumeChallenge2017. These accessories were designed to use very little support and print with very little errors, they could be adjusted for speed and 3d printer capability.
All stl's made my megamanxjac(which is me).

Prints need little to no support depending on your 3d printer. The ones that may are: Spoolboy’s belt, chest plate and shoe emblems.
Some of the prints need to be assembled using some sort of adhesive: Spoolboy’s shoe clips, PRINT3R’s bearings, circuit board plate, nozzle hand hot/cold.
*this was done to save time/space/material on printer, but they could be easily customized to remove the need for adhesive)
Belt based prints and chest based prints need cloth to be adhered to chest, back, and waistline. I used a 2 inch wide belt for the belt prints and 2 cm wide ribbons for the chest and back plates.

“Side kick meters” letters was adhered to the back of an empty spool and each arm and leg spool bracelets were attached by string or left over pla to the same empty spool. Spool back holders were glued to empty spool as well. (it is possible yet not recommended t

Foot spool bracelets are slightly scaled up larger arm spool bracelets with a cut down the middle to allow me to easily put them on and off, however one could simply make a larger spool bracelet to go over feet.
All designs were made for a big and tall person (5’11”; 42”), as such items will need to be scaled down for smaller persons. It is highly recommended to measure stl output files before printing. any tool capable of opening, measuring, and scaling stls should be able to view/measure/edit works.
Back circuit board is attached to Nozzle hand and Controller belt using wire.

Masks were purchased from party city to which the mask accessories were attached.

All designs were painted using acrylic and spray paints to give a super hero feel.

Images and video in project were created by megamanxjac and utilize the pictures listed in “picture sources”.

description.text:
[2018-01-25] Thanks to user groenewaldd's hints in the comments i have adapted the script to work for slic3r and Cura.

This is practically a remix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2614204.
The difference is that it has an overhang on the right side with a pointy cone on top of it. This is supposed to show how exact your printer prints (and cools) small pointy details.
You also can change the direction of where the highest and the lowest temperature will print: on top or on the bottom of the tower.

Usage example in Slic3r:

1. Generate the tower with openscad:

$ openscad tempTower.scad

Set the following variables in the openscad window to your liking: 

// temperature of the first lowest block
start_temp = 220;
// temperature of the last highest block
end_temp = 185;
// change in temperature between successively printed blocks
temp_step = 5;

Render and export the model to .stl and close openscad.

2. Generate gcode with Slic3r:

  1. Open the .stl file in Slic3r.
  2. Set layer height to 0.2mm. If not, multiply the skip and block parameters by (0.2mm/new_layer_height).
  3. Add the following to:
    "Printer Settings" -> "Custom G-code" -> "Before layer change G-code": 
    ;LAYER:[layer_num]

    This makes it possible for the 'setLayerTemperatur.py' script to recognize the single layers.

  4. Set the initial temperature in the filament settings. The pedestal on which the temperature tower stands will be printed with this temperature.
  5. Save the .gcode file of the model.

Attention: maybe you will have to disable the 'Enable variable layer height feature:' checkbox in the printer settings in order to avoid messing up the temperature distribution over the tower height!

3. Write temperature settings to gcode file with setLayerTemperatur.py:

  1. On the commandline:

    $ ./setLayerTemperatur.py -h
usage: setLayerTemperatur.py [-h] -s STARTTEMP -e ENDTEMP -t TEMPSTEP -f GCODEFILE

Sets the proper temperatures to the corresponding layers of a gcode file
exported from Slic3r. This allows the temperature tower to have different
temperatures per block.

optional arguments:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit

required arguments:
  -s STARTTEMP, --startTemp STARTTEMP
                        Temperature of the first (lowest) block.
  -e ENDTEMP, --endTemp ENDTEMP
                        Temperature of the last (highest) block.
  -t TEMPSTEP, --tempStep TEMPSTEP
                        Temperature change between successively printed
                        blocks.
  -f GCODEFILE, --gcodeFile GCODEFILE
                        The .gcode file to process.

    
$ ./setLayerTemperatur.py -s 240 -e 215 -t 5 -f tempTower_PETG_Black.gcode 
startTemp: 240
endTemp:   215
tempStep:  5
gcodeFile: "tempTower_PETG_Black.gcode"
outFile: "OUT_tempTower_PETG_Black.gcode"
step: -5
-> M104 S240
-> M104 S235
-> M104 S230
-> M104 S225
-> M104 S220
-> M104 S215
    By now the different temperatures should have been written to a new .gcode file that starts with "OUT_" and ends with the name of your old .gcode file. This file you can send to your printer and the tower should be printed out with the different temperature settings.

-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.
Hey guys.

Take a look to the new super awesome gun we created. She's name is Evelyne.
She has multiples firing configurations!

  • For a normal power of shooting,please, choose the "power" function, it will take power from that red liquid and fire death to your enemies.
  • Need more power? No problem, you can mix with our experimental bluish liquid for more devastation shooting damage. To do that you should set Evelyne to the "more power" option
    • What? Do you need to unleash all the powah!? No worries about that my friend. Set Evelyne to "MAX. Power" to unleash the true devastation to your enemies.
      -.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.-.

3D modeled using AutodeskFusion360 from an original design.

And now, how I print this?

1) Buy some jars. The design includes some jars to be printed if you can't find a suitable option. The sizes? 21mm diameter for the lateral jars and 30 mm diameter for the bigger one
2) Print everything and put aside all the gears, take a note that gear 1 has many components (gear 1.1, gear 1.2, gear 1.3...) and the same happens with the other gears.
3) Glue everything
4) Fill the jars! :)

Notes:

I suggest a better resolution (0.1) when printing the main body and the handle. I was in a hurry so I had to print at that resolution :(

You can use real cristal jar like I did, and real pipes :)

How to assembly the gears?

You need to check the filename of the .stl. I refered it to gear1.1. .2 .3 .4 to every part of the gear number 1, and so with the other ones.

So you need to get all the parts of each gear and assembly them with the gun. Make sure they are functional before glueing :)

Gear 1 and Gear 2 works for the fire mode selector. You don't need to glue this parts as they have to rotate.

Gear 3 goes inside the gun, you need to glue the axis with the gear. and put the axis through the hole at the main body. Then, when you have finished with glueing the main body, you can glue to this axis the "whirlwind.stl" one on each side of the axis. This way, as the gear rotates, so will do the whirlwind.

Gear 4. You have to glue the axis to the main body, but not to the gear itself.

Gear 5. You can pass the gear5.2 through the gear5.1 and then glue the geear 5.3 at the other side. Finally, glue the gear5.1 to the main body

So now you will have 5 rotation gears :)

description.text:
This is a chemical reaction separator-set intended to selectively separate two materials via an actuating and detaching rod from one side. The 'Outer.stl'' is fixed while the ''Inner.stl" is the thread-interfaced-surface intended to open and close the aperture with an actuating rod.

It was mainly designed as a method to separate effervescent tablets and water for a co2 water rocket. As the driving rod interfaces with the 'inner', once it rotates, the inner plate's flow holes becomes open and water will flow through the surrounding stators. Thus, water will enter from one chamber to the other chamber to react with the effervescent tablets, generating co2.

It is subject to change as further work is attributed for refinement.

The interfacing rod is (Not included, but it is just a rod with a + shaped cut out at the end. Think of it as an inverse of a Philips screwdriver and a screw) machined out of an aluminum extrusion found at most hardware stores. All the other parts were tested via a FDM printer on PLA.

remixed_from.title: Spool Holder For Prusa i3 6mm Frame

description.text: The external filament stand was finally getting on my nerves, and I didn't want to make my 3d printer any taller, so I tossed this together over a lunch break. It's intended to be placed over the right side of the top faceplate frame.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2mm

Infill:

20%

The Anet A8 has an 8mm acrylic frame, which is larger than the Prusa's top-bar both in height and depth. I scaled up a model from someone else in Openscad, and added a 6mm hole for a 6" bolt I had laying around. It's a tight fit for the bolt, and I could have used the 8mm bolt from the Anet's included, but alas, hindsight.

An 8" bolt might be a better option, since a very, very, very maximally volumetric build might actually tap a large-diameter spool.

The inner channel was supposed to be for the screwheads sticking up on the Anet, frame, but I just placed this to the right of the.

Future options:
1) make it wider.
2) shorten the rear lip, or add a channel to fit over the rear frame-stand.

The young people taking part in the camp were responding to the Designing Desire exhibition and the installation ‘She Who Sees the Unknown’, a reading room featuring images & text from middle eastern mythologies around Jiin's.

“The jinniya (female jinn) on which Allahyari’s work for Designing Desire is focused, Aeisheh Ghediseh (or Aisha) is said to create a crack on the male body as a sexual and erotic way to transform him into another being, forcing him to act as a conduit between worlds. When she possesses a man she does not completely take over the new host but opens him to a storm of incoming jnun and jinns and sorcerous particles of all kinds; making the man a gate for new demons, for sweeping cosmic data. This is why she is feared. And she never leaves — she always resides in the man to guarantee his total openness, which is not always pleas­ant.“

title: Sleeve Case for Raspberry Pi2/B+ with enlarged camera cable slot

description.text: This is yet another remix derived from walter's Raspberry Pi B+ sleeve. I liked the design and wanted to use it to be able to hang the Pi (running octoprint) off the side of my printrbot simple meta using ElmoC's supports (https://www.thingiverse.com/make:122064). But I needed a camera ribbon slot. Unfortunately I was not able to use the designs with a slot for the camera ribbon (from Doppeldutch and Galaxius) because I couldn't get enough access to the locking mechanism to hold the cable in place. I wasn't willing to risk a loose ribbon as I'd already destroyed a Pi camera what way. Since it looked like I just needed to delete a few bits, I fired up 3D-Slash (program motto should be 'make 3D models Minecraft style!') and deleted a few blocks to enlarge the camera ribbon slot. Since the internal grooves, especially at the far end, were too thin to fit my Pi, I enlarged them as well. While I still needed to use tweezers to do it, I was able to lock down the ribbon cable and that was all I cared about. Just a note I did need to enlarge the model to 101% to get the Pi to fit easily. If you have problems sliding the Pi into the sleeve, try that. Although you are limited to fairly coarse resolution, I enabled the 3D-Slash customization app so you can make the slot even wider if you like. If you need it enlarged further with a smoother resolution, let me know.

Introducing the Pill Packer 100x! Fill 100 "00" (750mg) and/or "0" (500mg) vegetable capsules at a time using whatever powder supplement you desire.

There are only three functioning parts: the pill holder, packer, and platform

Place the holder on top of the platform making sure is slides onto the cylinder and latches onto the notch. Then place a rubber band over the end of the notched side, if you plan on moving it around or packing them fairly hard. Place the capsules open end opposite the platform into the desired amount of slots then poor your powdered material over the capsules. Take a postcard, credit card or simply a piece of paper and wipe the excess off the top making sure to fill each hole as you move the card around. Take your packer line it up with each pill and press down firmly until the packer starts to sink down into the holes, pack to desired depth using small taps of the hand to press the powder down firmly.

Taking the pills out is simple, remove the rubber band and undo the bottom over a large container so your capsules don't fly everywhere. Then using the packer push the rest of the pills that remain out and apply the caps to each capsule.

description.text: I saw a few spool holders on here for the Prusa i3 that mounted to the top bar of the printer but since my printer has a 50mm tall top bar and the Prusa has a 40 mm top bar I designed my own. It's not pretty because I'm not very good at designing parts but it works. I made the cups for the tube half-circles with a radius of 9.5 mm to fit EMT conduit which I had lying around but I decided once I had the arms made to design a tube to fit instead of hacksawing some length of EMT because I was feeling lazy. The tube is 18mm in diameter. The stl files have already been run through netfabb, and the sldprt files from Solidworks 2014 are included. I only designed the arm once, I just used netfabb to mirror it for the second arm. So far this is working much better than the pegboard-arm-with-visegrips arrangement I had before! If you are worried about the tube coming out of the cups on the arms then you could put a zip tie around it but I don't think it will be an issue. I've run it without them for a few hours and it seems to hold the tube in just from the weight of the spool.

I liked the mounting option used by jmillerfo's Prusa i3 MK2S Print Server case which hooks the Pi low down on the M10 threaded chassis bars and cable tied in place. However, that project is for a Raspberry Pi Zero with a Li-po battery.

I combined these two models make this Raspberry Pi case, it mounts on the right hand side of the printer with the the Micro SD Card is toward the front of the printer and the USB / network cable toward the Z-axis stepper.

In the photos the camera is mounted to the right hand Z-axis stepper, my intention is to mount the camera to the heat bed once I get a longer camera cable.

It's probably worth pointing out that the case sits exactly on the surface when on the chassis bars. Our Prusa has only the felt feet so it should fit with those or anything taller under the feet.

description.text:
Create a fun articulated skeleton hand with fingers that you can control! This is great for costumes where you’ll have a skeleton hand / arm sticking out from a sleeve (like a grim reaper). After printing and assembly, you'll be able to curl the skeleton fingers using your actual fingers hidden in the sleeve. I've included both a left arm and a right arm (same thing mirrored). The attached zip file might be easiest to navigate.

For this project, you'll need some glue, thread or fishing line, and dental bands (I used these https://www.amazon.com/Sonic-Dental-X-Heavy-Orthodontic-Elastic/dp/B00A9IHMJA/ref=pd_lpo_vtph_194_bs_img_1?_encoding=UTF8&psc=1&refRID=36EW9KM54EE32TWBVVAD&dpID=31WcGksiafL&preST=_QL70_&dpSrc=detail). Print out the following to complete a hand:

1x of the following:

Pinkie 1, Pinkie 2, Pinkie 3, Pinkie 4
Ring 1, Ring 2, Ring 3, Ring 4
Middle 1, Middle 2, Middle 3, Middle 4
Index 1, Index 2, Index 3, Index 4
Thumb 1, Thumb 2, Thumb 3, Thumb 4,
Wrist,
Hand Brace

Step 1 - Sanding

As this requires a good amount of supports, you'll want to make sure you do a good job of sanding pieces down. I wasn't too worried about getting them smooth as I wanted a more grungy look anyways, but you won't want your thread / fishing line to get caught on anything sticking out. I used a 200 grit sand paper sheet to handle all of this.

Step 2 - Painting (Optional)

Though I printed mine in white, I wanted to give it a grungy dead look, so I ended up painting over the top of it. After sanding, I applied a pretty thin coat of XTC-3D to smooth out any other issues, and then gave it a light sand after it had dried. After that, I applied a coat of sprayable primer so my paint would have a good surface to attach to.

With my pieces ready to paint, I hit them all with a base bone yellow / cream coat, and then did some darker layers over the top to rough it up a bit. Since it's not going to really be seen up close, I wasn't too worried about the details and just wanted to give it some variation.

Step 3 - Gluing and Assembling Joints

Each of the fingers consists of 4 bones with little hinge joints between them. Each print file for a finger has a number. Index 1 connects to the wrist, Index 2 connects to Index 1, etc. The connectors should slide together so the holes line up and the blocks where the knuckle would be match somewhat. You'll want to take one of the Pegs and slide it into the hole so the finger bone has something to spin around. Take the Nut and add a little glue into the pocket in it and put it onto the other end of the Peg (that you pushed through) so it caps it and keeps the joint together. Make sure you don't accidentally glue the joint together as you want to make sure it can still rotate freely on the hinge. Repeat this for every finger, and all of the finger 1 pieces to the wrist.

The fingers on the hand should curl nicely at this point, but we want to make sure that when they're not under tension, the fingers snap back to an open position. For each knuckle where two finger bones come tougher (or the finger to the wrist), find the little blocks that meet up, and place on of the dental bands around them (1 around both). Repeat this for every knuckle. When you've done that, you should be able to curl a finger, and when you let go, it'll snap back into an open position.

Step 4 - Threading

The last step is to use your thread or fishing line to rig this entire thing so you can curl the fingers. You'll have one line for each finger, running from the Hoop piece (which your actual finger will go through) all the way to the tip of the skeleton finger, running through the little eye lets opposite the knuckles.

Start by threading your line through the eyelet on the hoop piece and tie it off. Next, take the other end of your line and thread it through the eye lets on the fingers, starting with the ones closest to the wrist and working your way to the tip (i.e. Index 1, then Index 2, then Index 3, then Index 4). At the tip of the finger before you tie it off, decide where the hoop should lie (and how long the lie should be) so it fits comfortably around your finger while still allowing you enough tension and range of motion to make the skeleton fingers. When you curl your own fingers, it'll pull down on the line through the eyelets curling each bone of the skeleton hand. When you've got your line length figured out, tie it off on the eyelet on the tip of the finger. Repeat this for each finger and thumb (it takes a little while, be patient).

Once you'll all threaded, you should be able to start using it. You should be able to put your arm inside the wrist brace and wrap your palm around the middle bar for support while doing this. It'll work best hidden inside a large cloak / sleeve so your real hand isn't visible, but the skeleton hand / arm bones are. Have fun!

description.text:
I love my cheap little CR-7 as it is relatively quiet and actually has outstanding print quality with a few tweaks. But sadly, it has no heated bed so it can only do PLA and PETG on a good, warm day. This adapter will fix that.

I'm a little hesitant to post this, only because it is designed to work with one particular heated bed, one I had purchased from Amazon (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01GEYT0B0/), and one that is a little sketchy. Do you see the two-star review on Amazon? Yeah, that's me. But my main gripe with it had to due with problems with the wiring harness, so as long as you check it over well (take out the pins from the connector and verify that they were crimped properly), then you should be alright. Probably. Hopefully.

EDIT 11-25-2017
The product does not seem to listed anymore. This might be temporary, but I did find a 24V version listed here: https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01GF04860/ However, you will have to provide power to that one with a separate power supply controlled by a relay or mosfet type device, otherwise it probably won't get too hot on only 12V.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker Original

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 works fine.

Infill:

Lots and lots. Make it solid.

Notes:

You will unfortunately need a bigger printer than the CR-7 to print this, so go ask your buddy to do it or have someone on 3DHubs do it. If you are really desperate then you can send it to my hub (https://www.3dhubs.com/service/51397) and I will print it for you and ship it to you.

I printed mine in PETG and it seems to be OK with the heat. I tried it up to 80C, pretty much the limit of the stock power supply. Polycarbonate would probably be the best if you can print with it.

EDIT 11-25-2017
The stock power supply was getting WAY too hot, so I replaced it with a 200W Meanwell. After that, I could get it over 100C, but then the heat melted my part :( I reprinted the part with Polymaker PC-plus (A polycarbonate-based filament) and shielded it with aluminum foil (taking care to insulate the components on the underside of the circuit board). This seems to have done the trick as I was printing at 110C in an enclosed environment and probably could have gone hotter.

Assembly

Assembly is really pretty straightforward.

1) Remove the standard bed by taking off the three adjustment screws.
2) Install the adapter as if it were the standard print bed.
3) Screw the aluminum plate and heated PCB onto the adapter using four M3 screws through the four inside holes of the plate.
4) Optionally install four screws and nuts on the four corners of the plate/PCB just to help pull them together and keep them flat.

That's it for the mechanical part. The electrical goes something like this:

1) Take the spare thermistor assembly included with the kit and clip off the actual thermistor. We are harvesting it for the connector and wire. If you have the appropriate connector, then skip this step.
2) Splice the cable assembly in step 1 onto the harness for the heated bed PCB. On mine, it was the first two pins (SIG and GND). It should not matter which is which.
3) Remove the middle wire from the harness. The one marked "5V". We don't need it.
4) Remove the control board cover on your CR-7.
5) Plug the SIG/GND plug we just made (which is actually the thermistor on the board) into the appropriate connector on the control board. It should be right next to the nozzle thermistor.
6) Wire the (+12V) wire of the heated bed to the (12V) terminal of the heated bed power connector on the control board (the unused green screw terminal thingy). Wire the (-HEAT) wire of the bed to the other terminal of the heated bed power connector (I'm sorry, I'm not sure how it was labeled.) If you accidentally switch the two wires then the bed should still work but the LED on the bed that indicates when it is heating will not work.
7) Put the cover back on your control board.

That's it, really. No firmware updates should be needed for the CR-7. It should just work. At least mine did. Yippee. If I were you, I would keep an eye on the stock power supply to make sure it does not blow up or burn your house down. You may want to purchase a good, metal-framed one. I can't remember if I'm using a stock one or not but it seems sufficient so far, but I'm not making any promises so don't sue me if you try it and it all ends in tears.
